Went into Addis on our way back from 4th street. I believe we stopped in there because there was no bar crowd. There were 10 in our group and we wanted to drink. The owner, Abbis (sp), took our order and then the magic happened. Our group consisted of five men and five women. The lady's drank beer and sat at a high table, and the men stood at the bar and drank bourbon. Our knowledge of bourbon was very minimal until Abbis, who is Ethiopian by the way, explained it in a very easy and  persuasive manner. We sampled several makers of bourbon and just listened to him speak about bourbon and different ways to enjoy it. I highly recommend this place for sampling bourbon. The prices are great and his selection covers many bourbon makers in Kentucky. At the first sight of this place, it does not look like a bourbon bar. So If you want ambiance and expensive fixtures, go to 4th street, and expect to pay double what Abbis charges. He has the knowledge and  selection to further your bourbon experience.  When we come back to Louisville, Addis bar and grill will be our first stop!

Addis has my favorite chicken curry in the city. The chicken is juicy, the hummus is creamy, and the portions are spot on (though I'd love more hummus but it's just a side). I go once a week for lunch and I don't think I'll ever get tired of it.

I typically go between the channa masala or Ethiopian vegetarian combo. Lots of food, great flavors, just the right amount of spice.  The channa is my favorite in town, including at purely Indian restaurants. Good tomato base with a slight smoky flavor adding to the ginger and garam masala. Really good. Small salad, hummus, pita and rice make up the meal.  As for he Ethiopian combo, all the traditional elements. Injera, Kik Alicha, misir wot, gomen are part of it.  Good spot for vegan, vegetarian or carnivores.

They have kabob meat and veg plates, but I think the real stars are the Ethiopian plates, served with delicious injera flatbread and richly flavored vegetables, lentils, or meats. I had the vegetarian, which had three colors of lentils, each tasting different and delicious, plus collards and cabbage. For the price, this place is a great deal and I would definitely be a regular visitor if I lived in the area.
